    <section id="about" class="section about">
        <div class="container">
            <div class="row">
                <!-- OLD
                <div class="col-sm-6">

                    <h3 class="section-title">About Us</h3>

                    <p>Generative Linguistics in the Old World (GLOW) is an international organization based in Europe facilitating the exchange and development of new ideas within generative grammar.</p>

                    <figure>
                        <img alt="" class="img-responsive" src="assets/images/about-us.jpg">
                    </figure>

                </div><!-- /.col-sm-6 -->

                <div class="col-sm-6">

                    <h3 class="section-title">Organising committee</h3>

                    <ul class="list-arrow-right">

                        <li>Marcel den Dikken (conference president)</li>
                        <li>Sónia Cyrino</li>
                        <li>Sónia Frota</li>
                        <li>Anabela Gonçalves</li>
                        <li>Tjerk Hagemeijer</li>
                        <li>Jakob Maché</li>
                        <li>Ana Lúcia Santos</li>
                    
                    </ul>

                </div><!-- /.col-sm-6 -->

                <div class="col-sm-6">

                    <h3 class="section-title multiple-title">Main Colloquium</h3>


                    <p>The 49th edition of GLOW will be held at the University of Lisbon, Portugal, from 22 to 25
March 2027 — 35 years after the 1992 Lisbon GLOW, where Richard Kayne presented the
fundamentals of his antisymmetry of syntax in his keynote address.</p>

                    <p>The main colloquium (22–24 March) has no designated theme. Contributions are welcome on
all topics, in all subdisciplines of the field, from any perspective compatible with generative
objectives. The organisers of GLOW49 would like to promote representation of work on
Portuguese and the Lusophone diaspora, as well as work on both spoken and signed
modalities of language.</p>

                    <p>Abstracts for the main colloquium are solicited for two types of presentation: (a) long presentations (max. 40 minutes) and (b) shorter presentations (max. 25 minutes). (Each presentation will be followed by a 10-minute question-and-answer period.) Abstract submissions are limited to a maximum of one single-authored and one co-authored abstract per person. Abstracts should be submitted as fully anonymized PDF documents that do not exceed two single-spaced pages (A4 with 2.5 cm margins or US letter with 1 inch margins on all sides), including examples, references and tables/figures, in a font no smaller than 12pt Times New Roman. Below the title, please provide a list of max. 5 keywords.</p> 


                                        <h4 class="section-title">Important dates:</h3>

